{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784446352311,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"id":"prt_f794a7baf0013H75VB2yPYBX80","messageID":"msg_f794a6dde001LvnePn6OmW3wrv","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784446690413,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"call_saxM6EhIv4gyMwjHyb8ATjOX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"Research source of truth","subagent_type":"deep-research","command":"/deep:research:auto","prompt":"Execute exactly ONE deep-research LEAF iteration, iteration 6 of 10, session fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t.\n\nFocus: Resolve Q5 source-of-truth and migration policy. Decide whether flat files, SQLite, or dual authority should own style content after cutover. Design staged bootstrap, shadow indexing/dual reads, parity metrics, cutover gates, rollback, repair/rebuild, delete/tombstone behavior, operator workflows, and whether/when flat files may stop being runtime retrieval inputs. Ground decisions in current sk-design manifest/hydration guarantees and system-spec-kit database/reindex/checkpoint patterns.\n\nRead lineage config/state/strategy/registry first. Write only iteration 006, exactly one canonical iteration state append, delta 006, and optional packet-local research.md inside the lineage. Do not modify reducer-owned files or any path outside the lineage. No subagents. Use exact file:line citations and canonical route proof. Forced max-iterations means continue after this iteration regardless of convergence telemetry. Return only the iteration completion report."},"output":"<task id=\"ses_086b5707effeRwNm9RDfmajyqS\" state=\"completed\">\n<task_result>\n## Iteration 6 Complete\n\n**Focus**: Q5 source-of-truth and migration policy  \n**Findings**: 8 findings (5 new, 3 partially new, 0 redundant)  \n**newInfoRatio**: 0.91  \n**Questions answered**: Q5  \n**Questions remaining**: 1 (Q1)  \n**Edge cases**: Ambiguous input resolved as query cutover—not full content migration  \n**Recommended next focus**: Resolve Q1’s minimum production topology and justify whether graph storage adds sufficient value beyond SQLite, FTS5, and vectors. Continue through iteration 10 regardless of convergence telemetry.\n\n**Files written**:\n- `research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md`\n- `research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl` (exactly one canonical iteration append)\n- `research/lineages/sol/deltas/iter-006.jsonl`\n\n**Verification**:\n- Iteration file exists: yes\n- JSONL iteration append count: 1\n- Delta canonical record matches state: yes\n- Findings citations complete: yes\n- Packet boundary respected: yes\n- Reducer-owned files untouched: yes\n- Subagents dispatched: no\n\n**Status**: complete\n</task_result>\n</task>","metadata":{"parentSessionId":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","sessionId":"ses_086b5707effeRwNm9RDfmajyqS","model":{"modelID":"gpt-5.6-sol-fast","providerID":"openai"},"truncated":false},"title":"Research source of truth","time":{"start":1784446357384,"end":1784446690407}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_04143158f7251434016a5c7d90d56881918c96cb9658b254c5"}},"id":"prt_f794a7dda001nUzYMluTbHNVul","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","messageID":"msg_f794a6dde001LvnePn6OmW3wrv"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784446691864,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"id":"prt_f794faa12001Gpt1CGPez0Qy4y","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","messageID":"msg_f794a6dde001LvnePn6OmW3wrv","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":219507,"input":2657,"output":263,"reasoning":11,"cache":{"write":0,"read":216576}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784446700032,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"id":"prt_f794fc9fd001SCrknVa6rI08uW","messageID":"msg_f794fafc9001zIUfOUe9maqQjr","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784446703144,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_YtJizZpcrpQIzyKVPHLgYkbK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 6: Source of Truth and Migration Policy\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: Resolve Q5 by choosing the post-cutover authority model and specifying bootstrap, shadow operation, parity gates, cutover, rollback, repair/rebuild, deletion, and operator workflows. Canonical route proof: this is the configured generation-1 session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, run 6 of 10, through `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md` as `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the agent contract is exactly one state-first, packet-locked LEAF iteration. The configured `stopPolicy` is `max-iterations`, so convergence remains telemetry and the workflow must continue after this iteration. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:27-41] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42]\n5: \n6: ## Findings\n7: 1. **Adopt one authority per plane, not dual authority over style content.** Flat style artifacts remain the authoring and content source of truth; the published SQLite generation becomes the sole runtime authority for discovery, eligibility, ranking, cards, and retrieval metadata. SQLite is a rebuildable materialized projection, not an independently editable copy of style content. This split preserves the current deterministic manifest contract, which reads and hashes the corpus, rejects a moving corpus, and derives one generation hash, while also removing corpus walks from the query path. It also preserves hydration's stronger guarantee: a request must match a committed generation, the live corpus must still serialize identically, paths must remain contained, rights must pass, and bytes must match the recorded digest. A database-only content authority would invalidate those guarantees; dual writes would create conflict resolution without a canonical winner. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-637] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: the source/artifact plane and retrieval/index plane can each have one authority without making the same field dual-authoritative]\n8: 2. **Use a five-stage migration with an immutable baseline.** Stage 0 freezes schema/normalization versions and captures the checked manifest, source aggregate hash, fixture-query outputs, and a rollback checkpoint. Stage 1 bootstraps a side database from one two-pass-verified, non-moving corpus snapshot and publishes nothing. Stage 2 keeps legacy file retrieval primary while every source change feeds shadow indexing and sampled dual reads. Stage 3 canaries the persistent adapter for selected callers while legacy remains an explicit rollback mode. Stage 4 makes SQLite the only normal query input after all gates pass; flat artifacts remain hydration and rebuild inputs. Stage 5 retires legacy query scanning only after the rollback window, but keeps an offline parity/repair command. The bootstrap must restart rather than publish if the post-build fingerprint changes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:640-678] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [INFERENCE: shadowing the current query response before switching its adapter gives a reversible compatibility boundary]\n9: 3. **Make parity multidimensional and separate compatibility from semantic improvement.** Census parity is exact equality of active IDs, UUID-to-slug mapping, statuses, artifact hashes, record count, and source generation. Eligibility parity is zero symmetric difference for every fixture/filter case. Legacy-adapter parity is byte-equivalent ordered cards, refusal/error codes, and generation mapping for the existing deterministic lexical endpoint. Native-v2 quality is measured separately with eligible-set Recall@K, top-5 overlap/order (or NDCG against curated judgments), per-channel attribution, and lexical-only fallback; semantic additions must not be misclassified as migration divergence. Operational parity tracks source-to-published-generation lag, shadow query errors, p50/p95 latency, hydration success/refusal-code parity, tombstone backlog, and vector coverage. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321] [INFERENCE: exact compatibility gates and relevance-improvement metrics must be distinct because semantic ranking intentionally may reorder otherwise eligible results]\n10: 4. **Cut over only on explicit, repeatable gates.** Require: exact census/eligibility/legacy-card parity over the complete deterministic fixture suite; zero unexplained generation mismatches or critical shadow errors over a defined observation window; no unconfirmed missing-style or tombstone backlog; lexical availability with vectors absent/degraded; p95 query latency materially below the current corpus-walk path; successful staged rebuild, cancel, crash-restart, checkpoint restore, and rollback drills; and operator sign-off on a machine-readable parity report tied to source hash, DB generation, schema version, and retrieval-profile version. The gate fails closed if the corpus changes during bootstrap or if the staged row count is incomplete, matching both current manifest verification and staged-shard publication safeguards. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:694-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:615-669] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:681-704] [INFERENCE: cutover evidence must bind the exact source and database generations being promoted]\n11: 5. **Rollback is an adapter/pointer reversal, never a reverse content write.** Before cutover, retain the prior DB generation, active-generation pointer, compatibility manifest, and checkpoint. A retrieval regression switches the adapter to legacy file retrieval or a prior DB generation only when that generation's source aggregate still matches the live corpus; otherwise rebuild from current files or use legacy current-file retrieval. Do not export stale DB rows back over flat files. Hydration remains fail-closed during rollback because it rechecks generation, live manifest, containment, rights, digest, and byte cap. The staged-reindex pattern demonstrates why publication must swap a complete adjacent file atomically and leave the active shard untouched on cancel/failure. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-629] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:654-704] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:302-370] [INFERENCE: a prior retrieval generation is safe only while its recorded source hash still describes the authoritative files]\n12: 6. **Repair derived state in place only when bounded; rebuild the complete database beside the active one otherwise.** Health/repair may regenerate FTS triggers/content, vector status, or a single style projection from authoritative files under one transaction. Structural corruption, schema migration, broad parity failure, or unknown drift requires a clean staged rebuild, integrity/census/parity checks, then an atomic generation-pointer/file switch. A checkpoint restore is not final truth when files have advanced: restore under a maintenance barrier, then reindex from files and retain a needs-rebuild sentinel until every derived surface succeeds. This follows system-spec-kit's transaction-wrapped clear-and-restore behavior and its explicit post-restore rebuild sentinel. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3081-3135] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3275-3310] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:661-748] [INFERENCE: restoring a derived index cannot supersede newer authoritative source bytes]\n13: 7. **Delete through the source plane and represent absence as a lifecycle, not an immediate hard delete.** An operator delete changes/removes the flat style artifacts and authoritative crawl membership; a DB-only delete is prohibited because a rebuild would resurrect the style. One missing scan records `pending_missing`; a second independent confirmed scan or explicit source delete creates an idempotent tombstone (`deleted_at`, source generation, reason), excludes it from retrieval, and preserves identity/provenance/relationship evidence. Hard purge follows a retention period, checkpoint, no-live-reference check, and successful rebuild/parity gate. Bulk destructive operations require explicit confirmation and should checkpoint first; soft-delete rows are naturally excluded by `deleted_at IS NULL`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:286-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-75] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:104-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:155-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:181-217] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:244-273]\n14: 8. **Expose a small operator lifecycle rather than hidden automatic authority changes.** Required workflows are: `status` (active/source generations, lag, schema/profile, channel health); `bootstrap --staging`; `sync`/`scan --dry-run`; `shadow-report`; `checkpoint create|list|restore`; `cutover preflight|promote`; `rollback`; `repair --derived`; `rebuild --staging`; and `tombstone list|confirm|purge`. Destructive and promotion commands require explicit confirmation, named checkpoint/generation, and an audit record; restores block concurrent deletes/index jobs. Normal query commands must never auto-fallback to a corpus walk after Stage 4 because that hides index failure and reintroduces the original latency/freshness cost. Flat files may stop being **runtime retrieval inputs** at Stage 4, but may not stop being runtime **hydration inputs** under the current contract; removing that dependency is a separate content-store migration requiring equivalent containment, rights, generation, digest, and byte-limit guarantees. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:82-100] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:116-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3088-3096] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-173] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: explicit lifecycle commands keep authority transitions observable, reversible, and auditable]\n15: \n16: ## Ruled Out\n17: - **SQLite as independently editable style-content authority:** incompatible with current file-backed hydration and creates an unimplemented authoring/export contract.\n18: - **Dual-write content authority:** no deterministic conflict winner; partial writes can make retrieval and hydrated bytes disagree.\n19: - **Permanent dual reads or corpus-walk fallback:** conceals index failures and preserves the performance/freshness problem.\n20: - **DB-only deletion:** authoritative files would resurrect the row on rebuild.\n21: - **Blind checkpoint restore as final state:** restored derived rows may be older than authoritative files and require reindex/parity verification.\n22: \n23: ## Dead Ends\n24: - Treating “source of truth” as one store for every plane is definitively eliminated for the current system. Content/authorship and runtime retrieval have different guarantees; forcing either flat files or SQLite to own both either retains query scans or breaks hydration.\n25: - Retiring flat files from hydration is not part of this migration. It requires a separately specified content-store contract and cannot be inferred from successful retrieval cutover.\n26: \n27: ## Edge Cases\n28: - Ambiguous input: “after cutover” could mean query cutover or complete content migration. This iteration selects the narrower evidenced interpretation: query cutover; complete content migration is deferred.\n29: - Contradictory evidence: none. Existing code consistently treats file bytes plus a checked generation as hydration authority, while SQLite patterns are derived/index lifecycle evidence.\n30: - Missing dependencies: no implemented style database or production traffic baseline exists, so numeric observation-window, latency, and relevance thresholds remain implementation-plan parameters; the required metric dimensions and zero-divergence invariants are resolved.\n31: - Partial success: none; Q5 is answered at architecture-policy level, while Q1 remains for a later iteration.\n32: \n33: ## Sources Consulted\n34: - `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42`\n35: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-41`\n36: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-712`\n37: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-205`\n38: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:164-370`\n39: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321`\n40: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-769`\n41: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:2977-3310`\n42: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-273`\n43: \n44: ## Assessment\n45: - New information ratio: 0.91 (5 fully new and 3 partially new findings yield 0.8125, plus the 0.10 simplicity bonus for resolving Q5, rounded to 0.91).\n46: - Questions addressed: Q5.\n47: - Questions answered: Q5 — flat files own authored/hydrated content; a published SQLite generation owns normal runtime retrieval after gated cutover; never dual-author the same content.\n48: - Forced continuation: iteration 6 cannot stop the loop because `stopPolicy=max-iterations` requires exactly 10 evidence-producing iterations. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-18]\n49: \n50: ## Reflection\n51: - What worked and why: Tracing the current manifest and hydration guards before applying system-spec-kit lifecycle patterns exposed the correct authority boundary: database retrieval can be promoted without weakening file-byte verification.\n52: - What did not work and why: A single-store framing could not satisfy both no-walk retrieval and current hydration guarantees; separating planes removed that false choice.\n53: - What I would do differently: In implementation planning, define concrete fixture inventory, observation duration, latency target, and curated relevance judgments before writing the migration code so every gate is executable from day one.\n54: \n55: ## Recommended Next Focus\n56: Resolve Q1 by choosing the minimum production topology now that authority is fixed: SQLite source/projection tables plus FTS5 and profile-addressed vectors as the retrieval core, with graph relationships either normalized in SQLite or justified as a separate runtime store. Pressure-test operational footprint, graph value, and failure isolation; continue through iteration 10 regardless of convergence telemetry.\n\n(End of file - total 56 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 6: Source of Truth and Migration Policy\n\n## Focus\nResolve Q5 by choosing the post-cutover authority model and specifying bootstrap, shadow operation, parity gates, cutover, rollback, repair/rebuild, deletion, and operator workflows. Canonical route proof: this is the configured generation-1 session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, run 6 of 10, through `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md` as `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the agent contract is exactly one state-first, packet-locked LEAF iteration. The configured `stopPolicy` is `max-iterations`, so convergence remains telemetry and the workflow must continue after this iteration. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:27-41] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42]\n\n## Findings\n1. **Adopt one authority per plane, not dual authority over style content.** Flat style artifacts remain the authoring and content source of truth; the published SQLite generation becomes the sole runtime authority for discovery, eligibility, ranking, cards, and retrieval metadata. SQLite is a rebuildable materialized projection, not an independently editable copy of style content. This split preserves the current deterministic manifest contract, which reads and hashes the corpus, rejects a moving corpus, and derives one generation hash, while also removing corpus walks from the query path. It also preserves hydration's stronger guarantee: a request must match a committed generation, the live corpus must still serialize identically, paths must remain contained, rights must pass, and bytes must match the recorded digest. A database-only content authority would invalidate those guarantees; dual writes would create conflict resolution without a canonical winner. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-637] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: the source/artifact plane and retrieval/index plane can each have one authority without making the same field dual-authoritative]\n2. **Use a five-stage migration with an immutable baseline.** Stage 0 freezes schema/normalization versions and captures the checked manifest, source aggregate hash, fixture-query outputs, and a rollback checkpoint. Stage 1 bootstraps a side database from one two-pass-verified, non-moving corpus snapshot and publishes nothing. Stage 2 keeps legacy file retrieval primary while every source change feeds shadow indexing and sampled dual reads. Stage 3 canaries the persistent adapter for selected callers while legacy remains an explicit rollback mode. Stage 4 makes SQLite the only normal query input after all gates pass; flat artifacts remain hydration and rebuild inputs. Stage 5 retires legacy query scanning only after the rollback window, but keeps an offline parity/repair command. The bootstrap must restart rather than publish if the post-build fingerprint changes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:640-678] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [INFERENCE: shadowing the current query response before switching its adapter gives a reversible compatibility boundary]\n3. **Make parity multidimensional and separate compatibility from semantic improvement.** Census parity is exact equality of active IDs, UUID-to-slug mapping, statuses, artifact hashes, record count, and source generation. Eligibility parity is zero symmetric difference for every fixture/filter case. Legacy-adapter parity is byte-equivalent ordered cards, refusal/error codes, and generation mapping for the existing deterministic lexical endpoint. Native-v2 quality is measured separately with eligible-set Recall@K, top-5 overlap/order (or NDCG against curated judgments), per-channel attribution, and lexical-only fallback; semantic additions must not be misclassified as migration divergence. Operational parity tracks source-to-published-generation lag, shadow query errors, p50/p95 latency, hydration success/refusal-code parity, tombstone backlog, and vector coverage. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321] [INFERENCE: exact compatibility gates and relevance-improvement metrics must be distinct because semantic ranking intentionally may reorder otherwise eligible results]\n4. **Cut over only on explicit, repeatable gates.** Require: exact census/eligibility/legacy-card parity over the complete deterministic fixture suite; zero unexplained generation mismatches or critical shadow errors over a defined observation window; no unconfirmed missing-style or tombstone backlog; lexical availability with vectors absent/degraded; p95 query latency materially below the current corpus-walk path; successful staged rebuild, cancel, crash-restart, checkpoint restore, and rollback drills; and operator sign-off on a machine-readable parity report tied to source hash, DB generation, schema version, and retrieval-profile version. The gate fails closed if the corpus changes during bootstrap or if the staged row count is incomplete, matching both current manifest verification and staged-shard publication safeguards. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:694-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:615-669] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:681-704] [INFERENCE: cutover evidence must bind the exact source and database generations being promoted]\n5. **Rollback is an adapter/pointer reversal, never a reverse content write.** Before cutover, retain the prior DB generation, active-generation pointer, compatibility manifest, and checkpoint. A retrieval regression switches the adapter to legacy file retrieval or a prior DB generation only when that generation's source aggregate still matches the live corpus; otherwise rebuild from current files or use legacy current-file retrieval. Do not export stale DB rows back over flat files. Hydration remains fail-closed during rollback because it rechecks generation, live manifest, containment, rights, digest, and byte cap. The staged-reindex pattern demonstrates why publication must swap a complete adjacent file atomically and leave the active shard untouched on cancel/failure. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-629] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:654-704] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:302-370] [INFERENCE: a prior retrieval generation is safe only while its recorded source hash still describes the authoritative files]\n6. **Repair derived state in place only when bounded; rebuild the complete database beside the active one otherwise.** Health/repair may regenerate FTS triggers/content, vector status, or a single style projection from authoritative files under one transaction. Structural corruption, schema migration, broad parity failure, or unknown drift requires a clean staged rebuild, integrity/census/parity checks, then an atomic generation-pointer/file switch. A checkpoint restore is not final truth when files have advanced: restore under a maintenance barrier, then reindex from files and retain a needs-rebuild sentinel until every derived surface succeeds. This follows system-spec-kit's transaction-wrapped clear-and-restore behavior and its explicit post-restore rebuild sentinel. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3081-3135] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3275-3310] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:661-748] [INFERENCE: restoring a derived index cannot supersede newer authoritative source bytes]\n7. **Delete through the source plane and represent absence as a lifecycle, not an immediate hard delete.** An operator delete changes/removes the flat style artifacts and authoritative crawl membership; a DB-only delete is prohibited because a rebuild would resurrect the style. One missing scan records `pending_missing`; a second independent confirmed scan or explicit source delete creates an idempotent tombstone (`deleted_at`, source generation, reason), excludes it from retrieval, and preserves identity/provenance/relationship evidence. Hard purge follows a retention period, checkpoint, no-live-reference check, and successful rebuild/parity gate. Bulk destructive operations require explicit confirmation and should checkpoint first; soft-delete rows are naturally excluded by `deleted_at IS NULL`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:286-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-75] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:104-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:155-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:181-217] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:244-273]\n8. **Expose a small operator lifecycle rather than hidden automatic authority changes.** Required workflows are: `status` (active/source generations, lag, schema/profile, channel health); `bootstrap --staging`; `sync`/`scan --dry-run`; `shadow-report`; `checkpoint create|list|restore`; `cutover preflight|promote`; `rollback`; `repair --derived`; `rebuild --staging`; and `tombstone list|confirm|purge`. Destructive and promotion commands require explicit confirmation, named checkpoint/generation, and an audit record; restores block concurrent deletes/index jobs. Normal query commands must never auto-fallback to a corpus walk after Stage 4 because that hides index failure and reintroduces the original latency/freshness cost. Flat files may stop being **runtime retrieval inputs** at Stage 4, but may not stop being runtime **hydration inputs** under the current contract; removing that dependency is a separate content-store migration requiring equivalent containment, rights, generation, digest, and byte-limit guarantees. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:82-100] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:116-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3088-3096] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-173] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: explicit lifecycle commands keep authority transitions observable, reversible, and auditable]\n\n## Ruled Out\n- **SQLite as independently editable style-content authority:** incompatible with current file-backed hydration and creates an unimplemented authoring/export contract.\n- **Dual-write content authority:** no deterministic conflict winner; partial writes can make retrieval and hydrated bytes disagree.\n- **Permanent dual reads or corpus-walk fallback:** conceals index failures and preserves the performance/freshness problem.\n- **DB-only deletion:** authoritative files would resurrect the row on rebuild.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md","text":"# Iteration 6: Source of Truth and Migration Policy\n\n## Focus\nResolve Q5 by choosing the post-cutover authority model and specifying bootstrap, shadow operation, parity gates, cutover, rollback, repair/rebuild, deletion, and operator workflows. Canonical route proof: this is the configured generation-1 session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, run 6 of 10, through `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md` as `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the agent contract is exactly one state-first, packet-locked LEAF iteration. The configured `stopPolicy` is `max-iterations`, so convergence remains telemetry and the workflow must continue after this iteration. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:27-41] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42]\n\n## Findings\n1. **Adopt one authority per plane, not dual authority over style content.** Flat style artifacts remain the authoring and content source of truth; the published SQLite generation becomes the sole runtime authority for discovery, eligibility, ranking, cards, and retrieval metadata. SQLite is a rebuildable materialized projection, not an independently editable copy of style content. This split preserves the current deterministic manifest contract, which reads and hashes the corpus, rejects a moving corpus, and derives one generation hash, while also removing corpus walks from the query path. It also preserves hydration's stronger guarantee: a request must match a committed generation, the live corpus must still serialize identically, paths must remain contained, rights must pass, and bytes must match the recorded digest. A database-only content authority would invalidate those guarantees; dual writes would create conflict resolution without a canonical winner. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-637] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: the source/artifact plane and retrieval/index plane can each have one authority without making the same field dual-authoritative]\n2. **Use a five-stage migration with an immutable baseline.** Stage 0 freezes schema/normalization versions and captures the checked manifest, source aggregate hash, fixture-query outputs, and a rollback checkpoint. Stage 1 bootstraps a side database from one two-pass-verified, non-moving corpus snapshot and publishes nothing. Stage 2 keeps legacy file retrieval primary while every source change feeds shadow indexing and sampled dual reads. Stage 3 canaries the persistent adapter for selected callers while legacy remains an explicit rollback mode. Stage 4 makes SQLite the only normal query input after all gates pass; flat artifacts remain hydration and rebuild inputs. Stage 5 retires legacy query scanning only after the rollback window, but keeps an offline parity/repair command. The bootstrap must restart rather than publish if the post-build fingerprint changes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:640-678] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:685-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [INFERENCE: shadowing the current query response before switching its adapter gives a reversible compatibility boundary]\n3. **Make parity multidimensional and separate compatibility from semantic improvement.** Census parity is exact equality of active IDs, UUID-to-slug mapping, statuses, artifact hashes, record count, and source generation. Eligibility parity is zero symmetric difference for every fixture/filter case. Legacy-adapter parity is byte-equivalent ordered cards, refusal/error codes, and generation mapping for the existing deterministic lexical endpoint. Native-v2 quality is measured separately with eligible-set Recall@K, top-5 overlap/order (or NDCG against curated judgments), per-channel attribution, and lexical-only fallback; semantic additions must not be misclassified as migration divergence. Operational parity tracks source-to-published-generation lag, shadow query errors, p50/p95 latency, hydration success/refusal-code parity, tombstone backlog, and vector coverage. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321] [INFERENCE: exact compatibility gates and relevance-improvement metrics must be distinct because semantic ranking intentionally may reorder otherwise eligible results]\n4. **Cut over only on explicit, repeatable gates.** Require: exact census/eligibility/legacy-card parity over the complete deterministic fixture suite; zero unexplained generation mismatches or critical shadow errors over a defined observation window; no unconfirmed missing-style or tombstone backlog; lexical availability with vectors absent/degraded; p95 query latency materially below the current corpus-walk path; successful staged rebuild, cancel, crash-restart, checkpoint restore, and rollback drills; and operator sign-off on a machine-readable parity report tied to source hash, DB generation, schema version, and retrieval-profile version. The gate fails closed if the corpus changes during bootstrap or if the staged row count is incomplete, matching both current manifest verification and staged-shard publication safeguards. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:694-712] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:615-669] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:681-704] [INFERENCE: cutover evidence must bind the exact source and database generations being promoted]\n5. **Rollback is an adapter/pointer reversal, never a reverse content write.** Before cutover, retain the prior DB generation, active-generation pointer, compatibility manifest, and checkpoint. A retrieval regression switches the adapter to legacy file retrieval or a prior DB generation only when that generation's source aggregate still matches the live corpus; otherwise rebuild from current files or use legacy current-file retrieval. Do not export stale DB rows back over flat files. Hydration remains fail-closed during rollback because it rechecks generation, live manifest, containment, rights, digest, and byte cap. The staged-reindex pattern demonstrates why publication must swap a complete adjacent file atomically and leave the active shard untouched on cancel/failure. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-629] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:654-704] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-291] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:302-370] [INFERENCE: a prior retrieval generation is safe only while its recorded source hash still describes the authoritative files]\n6. **Repair derived state in place only when bounded; rebuild the complete database beside the active one otherwise.** Health/repair may regenerate FTS triggers/content, vector status, or a single style projection from authoritative files under one transaction. Structural corruption, schema migration, broad parity failure, or unknown drift requires a clean staged rebuild, integrity/census/parity checks, then an atomic generation-pointer/file switch. A checkpoint restore is not final truth when files have advanced: restore under a maintenance barrier, then reindex from files and retain a needs-rebuild sentinel until every derived surface succeeds. This follows system-spec-kit's transaction-wrapped clear-and-restore behavior and its explicit post-restore rebuild sentinel. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3081-3135] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3275-3310] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:661-748] [INFERENCE: restoring a derived index cannot supersede newer authoritative source bytes]\n7. **Delete through the source plane and represent absence as a lifecycle, not an immediate hard delete.** An operator delete changes/removes the flat style artifacts and authoritative crawl membership; a DB-only delete is prohibited because a rebuild would resurrect the style. One missing scan records `pending_missing`; a second independent confirmed scan or explicit source delete creates an idempotent tombstone (`deleted_at`, source generation, reason), excludes it from retrieval, and preserves identity/provenance/relationship evidence. Hard purge follows a retention period, checkpoint, no-live-reference check, and successful rebuild/parity gate. Bulk destructive operations require explicit confirmation and should checkpoint first; soft-delete rows are naturally excluded by `deleted_at IS NULL`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:286-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-75] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:104-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:155-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:181-217] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:244-273]\n8. **Expose a small operator lifecycle rather than hidden automatic authority changes.** Required workflows are: `status` (active/source generations, lag, schema/profile, channel health); `bootstrap --staging`; `sync`/`scan --dry-run`; `shadow-report`; `checkpoint create|list|restore`; `cutover preflight|promote`; `rollback`; `repair --derived`; `rebuild --staging`; and `tombstone list|confirm|purge`. Destructive and promotion commands require explicit confirmation, named checkpoint/generation, and an audit record; restores block concurrent deletes/index jobs. Normal query commands must never auto-fallback to a corpus walk after Stage 4 because that hides index failure and reintroduces the original latency/freshness cost. Flat files may stop being **runtime retrieval inputs** at Stage 4, but may not stop being runtime **hydration inputs** under the current contract; removing that dependency is a separate content-store migration requiring equivalent containment, rights, generation, digest, and byte-limit guarantees. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:82-100] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:116-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3088-3096] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-173] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370] [INFERENCE: explicit lifecycle commands keep authority transitions observable, reversible, and auditable]\n\n## Ruled Out\n- **SQLite as independently editable style-content authority:** incompatible with current file-backed hydration and creates an unimplemented authoring/export contract.\n- **Dual-write content authority:** no deterministic conflict winner; partial writes can make retrieval and hydrated bytes disagree.\n- **Permanent dual reads or corpus-walk fallback:** conceals index failures and preserves the performance/freshness problem.\n- **DB-only deletion:** authoritative files would resurrect the row on rebuild.\n- **Blind checkpoint restore as final state:** restored derived rows may be older than authoritative files and require reindex/parity verification.\n\n## Dead Ends\n- Treating “source of truth” as one store for every plane is definitively eliminated for the current system. Content/authorship and runtime retrieval have different guarantees; forcing either flat files or SQLite to own both either retains query scans or breaks hydration.\n- Retiring flat files from hydration is not part of this migration. It requires a separately specified content-store contract and cannot be inferred from successful retrieval cutover.\n\n## Edge Cases\n- Ambiguous input: “after cutover” could mean query cutover or complete content migration. This iteration selects the narrower evidenced interpretation: query cutover; complete content migration is deferred.\n- Contradictory evidence: none. Existing code consistently treats file bytes plus a checked generation as hydration authority, while SQLite patterns are derived/index lifecycle evidence.\n- Missing dependencies: no implemented style database or production traffic baseline exists, so numeric observation-window, latency, and relevance thresholds remain implementation-plan parameters; the required metric dimensions and zero-divergence invariants are resolved.\n- Partial success: none; Q5 is answered at architecture-policy level, while Q1 remains for a later iteration.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n- `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-41`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-712`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-205`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:164-370`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-769`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:2977-3310`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-273`\n\n## Assessment\n- New information ratio: 0.91 (5 fully new and 3 partially new findings yield 0.8125, plus the 0.10 simplicity bonus for resolving Q5, rounded to 0.91).\n- Questions addressed: Q5.\n- Questions answered: Q5 — flat files own authored/hydrated content; a published SQLite generation owns normal runtime retrieval after gated cutover; never dual-author the same content.\n- Forced continuation: iteration 6 cannot stop the loop because `stopPolicy=max-iterations` requires exactly 10 evidence-producing iterations. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-18]\n\n## Reflection\n- What worked and why: Tracing the current manifest and hydration guards before applying system-spec-kit lifecycle patterns exposed the correct authority boundary: database retrieval can be promoted without weakening file-byte verification.\n- What did not work and why: A single-store framing could not satisfy both no-walk retrieval and current hydration guarantees; separating planes removed that false choice.\n- What I would do differently: In implementation planning, define concrete fixture inventory, observation duration, latency target, and curated relevance judgments before writing the migration code so every gate is executable from day one.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\nResolve Q1 by choosing the minimum production topology now that authority is fixed: SQLite source/projection tables plus FTS5 and profile-addressed vectors as the retrieval core, with graph relationships either normalized in SQLite or justified as a separate runtime store. Pressure-test operational footprint, graph value, and failure isolation; continue through iteration 10 regardless of convergence telemetry.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":56,"totalLines":56,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md","time":{"start":1784446703138,"end":1784446703142}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08e98fef2b68e390016a5c7eef052081918d93f024edbc68fd"}},"id":"prt_f794fd5dd001WFslZcaG4fKGV1","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","messageID":"msg_f794fafc9001zIUfOUe9maqQjr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784446703225,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_uq7LbWiClLaEsJKrbfJmxi9w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deltas/iter-006.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deltas/iter-006.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":6,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Resolve Q5 source-of-truth and migration policy: authority boundaries, staged bootstrap/shadow reads, parity gates, cutover, rollback, repair/rebuild, deletion, and operator workflows.\",\"findingsCount\":8,\"newInfoRatio\":0.91,\"noveltyJustification\":\"5 of 8 findings were fully new and 3 partially new; resolving Q5 earned the 0.10 simplicity bonus (0.8125 + 0.10, rounded to 0.91).\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Q5\",\"Q1\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Q5\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"SQLite as independently editable style-content authority\",\"Dual-write content authority\",\"Permanent dual reads or corpus-walk fallback\",\"DB-only deletion\",\"Blind checkpoint restore as final state\"],\"focusTrack\":\"migration-authority\",\"edgeCase\":\"none\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"memory_match_triggers\",\"Skill\",\"Grep\",\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\",\"ApplyPatch\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\".opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-41\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-7\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:7-90\",\"research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:1-75\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-712\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-205\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:164-370\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-769\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:2977-3310\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-273\",\"command: date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-19T07:35:04Z\",\"durationMs\":135000,\"graphEvents\":[]}\n2: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F1\",\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain content authority while the published SQLite generation becomes sole normal-query authority; the same content is never dual-authoritative.\",\"novelty\":\"full\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:584-712\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-370\"]}\n3: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F2\",\"summary\":\"Migration uses baseline, staged bootstrap, shadow dual reads, canary, query cutover, then retirement of legacy query scanning.\",\"novelty\":\"full\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:640-712\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155\"]}\n4: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F3\",\"summary\":\"Parity separates exact census/eligibility/legacy compatibility from native-v2 relevance and operational metrics.\",\"novelty\":\"full\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:119-155\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-370\"]}\n5: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F4\",\"summary\":\"Cutover requires source-bound reports plus parity, health, latency, tombstone, rebuild, restore, and rollback drills.\",\"novelty\":\"full\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:694-712\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:615-704\"]}\n6: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F5\",\"summary\":\"Rollback reverses an adapter or generation pointer and never writes derived database rows back over authoritative files.\",\"novelty\":\"partial\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:586-704\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:225-370\"]}\n7: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F6\",\"summary\":\"Bounded derived repair is distinct from staged full rebuild; checkpoint restore must reindex newer files and preserve a rebuild sentinel until healthy.\",\"novelty\":\"partial\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3081-3310\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/embedders/reindex.ts:661-748\"]}\n8: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F7\",\"summary\":\"Deletes originate in the source plane, pass through confirmed tombstones, and hard-purge only after retention, checkpoint, and parity gates.\",\"novelty\":\"partial\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/incremental-index.ts:283-321\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:54-273\"]}\n9: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-F8\",\"summary\":\"Operators need explicit status/bootstrap/sync/shadow/checkpoint/cutover/rollback/repair/rebuild/tombstone workflows; flat files retire from query input but not current hydration.\",\"novelty\":\"full\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/handlers/memory-bulk-delete.ts:82-127\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp-server/lib/storage/checkpoints.ts:3088-3096\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/hydrate.mjs:315-370\"]}\n10: {\"type\":\"invariant\",\"iteration\":6,\"id\":\"I006-INV1\",\"summary\":\"No database generation may be promoted unless its recorded source aggregate identifies the verified authoritative flat-file snapshot used to build it.\"}\n11: {\"type\":\"ruled_out\",\"iteration\":6,\"approach\":\"Dual-authoritative flat files and SQLite\",\"reason\":\"No deterministic conflict winner and current hydration verifies live file bytes.\"}\n12: {\"type\":\"observation\",\"iteration\":6,\"summary\":\"Q5 is answered, but max-iterations stop policy requires iterations 7-10 regardless of the 0.91 novelty telemetry.\"}\n\n(End of file - total 12 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":6,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Resolve Q5 source-of-truth and migration policy: authority boundaries, staged bootstrap/shadow reads, parity gates, cutover, rollback, repair/rebuild, deletion, and operator workflows.\",\"findingsCount\":8,\"newInfoRatio\":0.91,\"noveltyJustification\":\"5 of 8 findings were fully new and 3 partially new; resolving Q5 earned the 0.10 simplicity bonus (0.8125 + 0.10, rounded to 0.91).\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Q5\",\"Q1\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Q5\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"SQLite as independently editable style-content authority\",\"Dual-write content authority\",\"Permanent dual reads or corpus-walk fallback\",\"DB-only deletion\",\"Blind checkpoint restore as final state\"],\"focusTrack\":\"migration-authority\",\"edgeCase\":\"none\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"memory_match_triggers\",\"Skill\",\"Grep\",\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\",\"ApplyPatch\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\".opencode/agents/deep-research.md:24-42\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:3-41\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl