{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784447112000,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"call_2FShusHT9aY1QNTYpbZMTkXw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"Evaluate graph topology","subagent_type":"deep-research","command":"/deep:research:auto","prompt":"Execute exactly ONE deep-research LEAF iteration, iteration 7 of 10, session fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t.\n\nFocus: Resolve Q1 by comparing SQLite+FTS+embeddings, a graph database, and a hybrid. Inspect the named in-repo graph implementations `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts` and `coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts` plus their direct schema/query contracts. Determine what style relationships actually need graph traversal, whether normalized SQLite edge tables suffice, operational/failure trade-offs, and the minimum production topology now versus optional future graph projection. Produce a clear technology recommendation with conditions that would justify graph promotion.\n\nRead lineage state first. Write only iteration 007, one canonical state append, delta 007, and optional progressive research.md inside the lineage. Never modify reducer-owned files or outside paths. No subagents. Cite exact files/lines, include route proof, and treat convergence as telemetry only. Return only the iteration completion report."},"output":"<task id=\"ses_086af4af1ffe2OyeOh9VMXOPhE\" state=\"completed\">\n<task_result>\n## Iteration 7 Complete\n\n**Focus**: Minimum production topology and graph-promotion conditions  \n**Findings**: 8 findings (7 new, 1 partially new, 0 redundant)  \n**newInfoRatio**: 1.00  \n**Questions answered**: Q1  \n**Questions remaining**: 0  \n**Edge cases**: Ambiguous “graph database” terminology resolved  \n**Recommended next focus**: Pressure-test topology operations, concurrency, latency, corruption boundaries, and measurable promotion SLOs.\n\n**Files written**:\n- `research/iterations/iteration-007.md`\n- `research/deep-research-state.jsonl` — exactly one iteration record appended\n- `research/deltas/iter-007.jsonl`\n- `research/research.md` — progressively updated\n\n**Verification**:\n- Iteration file exists: yes\n- JSONL iteration append count: 1\n- State/delta canonical records equivalent: yes\n- Findings citations complete: yes\n- Route proof present: yes\n- Packet boundary respected: yes\n- Reducer-owned files untouched: yes\n\n**Status**: complete\n</task_result>\n</task>","metadata":{"parentSessionId":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","sessionId":"ses_086af4af1ffe2OyeOh9VMXOPhE","model":{"modelID":"gpt-5.6-sol-fast","providerID":"openai"},"truncated":false},"title":"Evaluate graph topology","time":{"start":1784446760207,"end":1784447111997}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08e8995ee1fd02a7016a5c7f23c9508191ad82de3c192673e0"}},"id":"prt_f7950a411001PS5fdk8dTB3Mj7","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","messageID":"msg_f79508e40001fiVZEHrjSJSMWY"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784447113411,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"id":"prt_f795618be001E1827ycKdL1gAn","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","messageID":"msg_f79508e40001fiVZEHrjSJSMWY","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":227596,"input":2549,"output":263,"reasoning":16,"cache":{"write":0,"read":224768}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784447119055,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"id":"prt_f79562ecc001olqWZba0ayqqW1","messageID":"msg_f79561e990013aueidIUr8osr5","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784447122041,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_MxQhSHghbOLFUrgZ0V8kPJQG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-007.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-007.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 7: Minimum Topology and Graph Promotion Boundary\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: Resolve Q1 by comparing SQLite + FTS5 + embeddings, a dedicated graph database, and a hybrid with a graph projection. The selected interpretation of “graph database” is a dedicated graph engine/service, because the two named in-repo “graph database” implementations are themselves SQLite adjacency projections. Route proof: the lineage config identifies session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, `lineageMode: new`, and the packet-local artifact root; six prior iteration records make this iteration 7. [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:18-41] [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:3-8] Resolved route: `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the deep-research agent definition was loaded by dispatch.\n5: \n6: ## Findings\n7: 1. The source corpus already contains a directed, explained relationship candidate: `designSystem.similar[]` stores a `business` target label plus `why`. However, the strict retrieval projection omits this field—`STYLE_KEYS` contains no relationship member—while its indexed relatedness is currently derived from capabilities, token axes, theme, industry, and text patterns. This means relationships need ingestion and identity resolution before they can participate in retrieval, not a new store first. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405]\n8: 2. The relationship payload is too unresolved for authoritative graph traversal today. A bounded corpus scan found 1,283 of 1,290 styles with 5,812 `similar` references, but only 2,269 (39.04%) resolved to one canonical style name; 440 (7.57%) were ambiguous and 3,103 (53.39%) unresolved. The resolvable undirected projection has 317 isolates and 325 components, although one component contains 954 styles. Preserve raw labels and rationale with `resolution_status`; do not silently turn names into canonical edges. [SOURCE: command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory, 2026-07-19T07:42:08Z] [INFERENCE: the measured ambiguity requires nullable canonical targets and explicit resolution provenance]\n9: 3. Both named in-repo graph implementations validate that normalized SQLite edge tables are a production graph representation at this scale. Council declares itself a runtime-owned SQLite derived projection, then uses composite namespace node/edge primary keys, foreign keys, source/target/relation indexes, WAL, and transactional batch upserts. Coverage uses the same adjacency shape, composite foreign keys and indexes, WAL, schema versioning, and transactional writes. Neither implementation depends on a native graph server. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:119-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:195-223] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:658-687] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:318-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:935-974]\n10: 4. The direct query contracts are predominantly indexed one-hop predicates and aggregates: incoming/outgoing support, unresolved-edge checks, contradiction joins, coverage gaps, and degree/weight ranking. Multi-hop behavior is exceptional and bounded: council performs application-side BFS only for evidence/support/derivation chains; coverage performs bounded application-side BFS for provenance and in-memory DAG depth for signals. Therefore graph-shaped data does not imply a dedicated graph engine. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:191-227] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-642] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-469]\n11: 5. Style retrieval presently needs only: (a) direct curated `SIMILAR_TO` neighbors with rationale, (b) shared-facet/axis/industry joins, and (c) semantic nearest neighbors from embeddings. Similarity is not transitive, so “A similar to B similar to C” must not become a default relevance claim. Direct neighbors and shared attributes are one-hop SQL joins; vector similarity is already a ranked projection. A normalized `style_relationships(source_style_id, relation, target_style_id NULL, raw_target_label, rationale, resolution_status, confidence, source_hash, generation_id)` table with indexes on `(source_style_id, relation)` and `(target_style_id, relation)` is sufficient now. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405] [INFERENCE: similarity's non-transitivity and the in-repo indexed-adjacency query pattern bound current traversal to one hop]\n12: 6. **Technology recommendation:** ship SQLite + FTS5 + profile-addressed embeddings, with normalized relational edges in the same published SQLite generation. This minimum topology keeps eligibility, metadata, FTS, relationship identity, and generation publication in one transactional snapshot; the vector shard remains a rebuildable generation/profile-bound projection. Compared with it, a dedicated graph database adds native variable-path querying but also a second availability domain, schema/migration surface, backup/restore path, authentication/runtime dependency, projection lag, and cross-store cutover failure modes without a demonstrated style query that benefits. A hybrid with a graph projection preserves relational authority but pays those duplication costs, so it is an optional future topology, not the launch topology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:135-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:252-298] [INFERENCE: combining iteration-4 atomic generation publication with the observed derived-projection lifecycle minimizes current failure domains]\n13: 7. The optional future graph must be a rebuildable, generation-stamped projection from relational `style_relationships`, never a second authority. Its failure should disable graph-only ranking/exploration while structured + FTS + vector retrieval remains available; publication must expose projection generation and lag, and rebuild/rollback must be idempotent. This mirrors the council graph's explicit derived-index ownership and namespace cleanup, rather than dual-writing user-authored truth. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:690-705] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:271-298] [INFERENCE: a disposable projection prevents graph outage or lag from corrupting the authoritative generation]\n14: 8. Promote to a dedicated graph projection only when all relevant gates hold: a product query requires explainable variable-depth paths (normally 3+ hops), path constraints, community/centrality algorithms, or cross-entity traversal that cannot be expressed as bounded joins; an indexed SQLite/recursive-CTE benchmark misses the defined p95 SLO at representative edge volume; graph-derived ranking materially improves an offline relevance set; canonical target resolution is identity-based and high-quality (recommended ≥95%, with ambiguity quarantined); and operators have generation parity, lag alarms, rebuild, restore, rollback, and graph-down fallback drills. Until then, graph traversal is an unmeasured capability rather than user value. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:747-805] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:513-547] [INFERENCE: promotion must be justified by workload, relevance, data quality, and operability rather than graph-shaped nouns]\n15: \n16: ## Ruled Out\n17: - Dedicated graph database in the minimum topology: no current style query needs native variable-depth traversal, and the corpus relationship targets are mostly unresolved.\n18: - Treating every `similar.business` label as a canonical edge: 60.96% are ambiguous or unresolved by unique canonical name.\n19: - Materializing shared facet or embedding similarity as authoritative graph edges: both are derived query signals and would create avoidable churn.\n20: - Default transitive similarity expansion: the relationship semantics do not support transitivity.\n21: \n22: ## Dead Ends\n23: - “Graph data requires a graph server” is eliminated by both named in-repo implementations: they use indexed SQLite adjacency tables and bounded application/SQL queries.\n24: - Evaluating native graph algorithms before canonical relationship resolution and a concrete multi-hop product query would benchmark an invented workload.\n25: \n26: ## Edge Cases\n27: - Ambiguous input: “graph database” could mean any node/edge model or a dedicated graph engine. The comparison uses the dedicated-engine meaning; the in-repo SQLite graph projections are treated as evidence for the relational-edge option.\n28: - Contradictory evidence: none.\n29: - Missing dependencies: none; no external graph-service benchmark was needed because selecting one is a stated non-goal and no qualifying workload exists.\n30: - Partial success: none.\n31: \n32: ## Sources Consulted\n33: - `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6,119-176,195-223,658-705`\n34: - `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-227`\n35: - `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-370,935-974`\n36: - `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-805`\n37: - `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-547`\n38: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73,391-405`\n39: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118`\n40: - `command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory, 2026-07-19T07:42:08Z`\n41: \n42: ## Assessment\n43: - New information ratio: 1.0 (7 fully new findings and 1 partially new schema extension yield 0.9375; resolving Q1 adds the 0.10 simplicity bonus, capped at 1.0).\n44: - Questions addressed: Q1.\n45: - Questions answered: Q1.\n46: - Convergence: telemetry only; the max-iterations policy still requires iterations 8-10.\n47: \n48: ## Reflection\n49: - What worked and why: reading the graph storage and query modules together separated graph data modeling from graph-engine necessity; quantifying the corpus's actual `similar` payload prevented a topology recommendation based on assumed relationship quality.\n50: - What did not work and why: a broad relationship-key search was noisy because `similar` appears in nearly every canonical file; the bounded parser converted that noise into resolution and topology measurements.\n51: - What I would do differently: benchmark a concrete bounded SQLite relationship query only after target normalization rules and a user-facing multi-hop query are specified; benchmarking synthetic traversal now would manufacture demand.\n52: \n53: ## Recommended Next Focus\n54: Pressure-test the recommended single-generation topology against concurrency, database/vector file placement, startup/cold-cache latency, corruption boundaries, backup size, and graph-down-equivalent degradation; define measurable SLOs that could activate the graph-promotion gates without reopening Q1 by preference.\n\n(End of file - total 54 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 7: Minimum Topology and Graph Promotion Boundary\n\n## Focus\nResolve Q1 by comparing SQLite + FTS5 + embeddings, a dedicated graph database, and a hybrid with a graph projection. The selected interpretation of “graph database” is a dedicated graph engine/service, because the two named in-repo “graph database” implementations are themselves SQLite adjacency projections. Route proof: the lineage config identifies session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, `lineageMode: new`, and the packet-local artifact root; six prior iteration records make this iteration 7. [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:18-41] [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:3-8] Resolved route: `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the deep-research agent definition was loaded by dispatch.\n\n## Findings\n1. The source corpus already contains a directed, explained relationship candidate: `designSystem.similar[]` stores a `business` target label plus `why`. However, the strict retrieval projection omits this field—`STYLE_KEYS` contains no relationship member—while its indexed relatedness is currently derived from capabilities, token axes, theme, industry, and text patterns. This means relationships need ingestion and identity resolution before they can participate in retrieval, not a new store first. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405]\n2. The relationship payload is too unresolved for authoritative graph traversal today. A bounded corpus scan found 1,283 of 1,290 styles with 5,812 `similar` references, but only 2,269 (39.04%) resolved to one canonical style name; 440 (7.57%) were ambiguous and 3,103 (53.39%) unresolved. The resolvable undirected projection has 317 isolates and 325 components, although one component contains 954 styles. Preserve raw labels and rationale with `resolution_status`; do not silently turn names into canonical edges. [SOURCE: command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory, 2026-07-19T07:42:08Z] [INFERENCE: the measured ambiguity requires nullable canonical targets and explicit resolution provenance]\n3. Both named in-repo graph implementations validate that normalized SQLite edge tables are a production graph representation at this scale. Council declares itself a runtime-owned SQLite derived projection, then uses composite namespace node/edge primary keys, foreign keys, source/target/relation indexes, WAL, and transactional batch upserts. Coverage uses the same adjacency shape, composite foreign keys and indexes, WAL, schema versioning, and transactional writes. Neither implementation depends on a native graph server. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:119-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:195-223] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:658-687] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:318-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:935-974]\n4. The direct query contracts are predominantly indexed one-hop predicates and aggregates: incoming/outgoing support, unresolved-edge checks, contradiction joins, coverage gaps, and degree/weight ranking. Multi-hop behavior is exceptional and bounded: council performs application-side BFS only for evidence/support/derivation chains; coverage performs bounded application-side BFS for provenance and in-memory DAG depth for signals. Therefore graph-shaped data does not imply a dedicated graph engine. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:191-227] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-642] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-469]\n5. Style retrieval presently needs only: (a) direct curated `SIMILAR_TO` neighbors with rationale, (b) shared-facet/axis/industry joins, and (c) semantic nearest neighbors from embeddings. Similarity is not transitive, so “A similar to B similar to C” must not become a default relevance claim. Direct neighbors and shared attributes are one-hop SQL joins; vector similarity is already a ranked projection. A normalized `style_relationships(source_style_id, relation, target_style_id NULL, raw_target_label, rationale, resolution_status, confidence, source_hash, generation_id)` table with indexes on `(source_style_id, relation)` and `(target_style_id, relation)` is sufficient now. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405] [INFERENCE: similarity's non-transitivity and the in-repo indexed-adjacency query pattern bound current traversal to one hop]\n6. **Technology recommendation:** ship SQLite + FTS5 + profile-addressed embeddings, with normalized relational edges in the same published SQLite generation. This minimum topology keeps eligibility, metadata, FTS, relationship identity, and generation publication in one transactional snapshot; the vector shard remains a rebuildable generation/profile-bound projection. Compared with it, a dedicated graph database adds native variable-path querying but also a second availability domain, schema/migration surface, backup/restore path, authentication/runtime dependency, projection lag, and cross-store cutover failure modes without a demonstrated style query that benefits. A hybrid with a graph projection preserves relational authority but pays those duplication costs, so it is an optional future topology, not the launch topology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:135-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:252-298] [INFERENCE: combining iteration-4 atomic generation publication with the observed derived-projection lifecycle minimizes current failure domains]\n7. The optional future graph must be a rebuildable, generation-stamped projection from relational `style_relationships`, never a second authority. Its failure should disable graph-only ranking/exploration while structured + FTS + vector retrieval remains available; publication must expose projection generation and lag, and rebuild/rollback must be idempotent. This mirrors the council graph's explicit derived-index ownership and namespace cleanup, rather than dual-writing user-authored truth. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:690-705] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:271-298] [INFERENCE: a disposable projection prevents graph outage or lag from corrupting the authoritative generation]\n8. Promote to a dedicated graph projection only when all relevant gates hold: a product query requires explainable variable-depth paths (normally 3+ hops), path constraints, community/centrality algorithms, or cross-entity traversal that cannot be expressed as bounded joins; an indexed SQLite/recursive-CTE benchmark misses the defined p95 SLO at representative edge volume; graph-derived ranking materially improves an offline relevance set; canonical target resolution is identity-based and high-quality (recommended ≥95%, with ambiguity quarantined); and operators have generation parity, lag alarms, rebuild, restore, rollback, and graph-down fallback drills. Until then, graph traversal is an unmeasured capability rather than user value. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:747-805] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:513-547] [INFERENCE: promotion must be justified by workload, relevance, data quality, and operability rather than graph-shaped nouns]\n\n## Ruled Out\n- Dedicated graph database in the minimum topology: no current style query needs native variable-depth traversal, and the corpus relationship targets are mostly unresolved.\n- Treating every `similar.business` label as a canonical edge: 60.96% are ambiguous or unresolved by unique canonical name.\n- Materializing shared facet or embedding similarity as authoritative graph edges: both are derived query signals and would create avoidable churn.\n- Default transitive similarity expansion: the relationship semantics do not support transitivity.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-007.md","text":"# Iteration 7: Minimum Topology and Graph Promotion Boundary\n\n## Focus\nResolve Q1 by comparing SQLite + FTS5 + embeddings, a dedicated graph database, and a hybrid with a graph projection. The selected interpretation of “graph database” is a dedicated graph engine/service, because the two named in-repo “graph database” implementations are themselves SQLite adjacency projections. Route proof: the lineage config identifies session `fanout-sol-1784444104016-7oed3t`, `lineageMode: new`, and the packet-local artifact root; six prior iteration records make this iteration 7. [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:18-41] [SOURCE: research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:3-8] Resolved route: `mode=research target_agent=deep-research`; the deep-research agent definition was loaded by dispatch.\n\n## Findings\n1. The source corpus already contains a directed, explained relationship candidate: `designSystem.similar[]` stores a `business` target label plus `why`. However, the strict retrieval projection omits this field—`STYLE_KEYS` contains no relationship member—while its indexed relatedness is currently derived from capabilities, token axes, theme, industry, and text patterns. This means relationships need ingestion and identity resolution before they can participate in retrieval, not a new store first. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405]\n2. The relationship payload is too unresolved for authoritative graph traversal today. A bounded corpus scan found 1,283 of 1,290 styles with 5,812 `similar` references, but only 2,269 (39.04%) resolved to one canonical style name; 440 (7.57%) were ambiguous and 3,103 (53.39%) unresolved. The resolvable undirected projection has 317 isolates and 325 components, although one component contains 954 styles. Preserve raw labels and rationale with `resolution_status`; do not silently turn names into canonical edges. [SOURCE: command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory, 2026-07-19T07:42:08Z] [INFERENCE: the measured ambiguity requires nullable canonical targets and explicit resolution provenance]\n3. Both named in-repo graph implementations validate that normalized SQLite edge tables are a production graph representation at this scale. Council declares itself a runtime-owned SQLite derived projection, then uses composite namespace node/edge primary keys, foreign keys, source/target/relation indexes, WAL, and transactional batch upserts. Coverage uses the same adjacency shape, composite foreign keys and indexes, WAL, schema versioning, and transactional writes. Neither implementation depends on a native graph server. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:119-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:195-223] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:658-687] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-298] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:318-370] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:935-974]\n4. The direct query contracts are predominantly indexed one-hop predicates and aggregates: incoming/outgoing support, unresolved-edge checks, contradiction joins, coverage gaps, and degree/weight ranking. Multi-hop behavior is exceptional and bounded: council performs application-side BFS only for evidence/support/derivation chains; coverage performs bounded application-side BFS for provenance and in-memory DAG depth for signals. Therefore graph-shaped data does not imply a dedicated graph engine. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:191-227] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-642] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-469]\n5. Style retrieval presently needs only: (a) direct curated `SIMILAR_TO` neighbors with rationale, (b) shared-facet/axis/industry joins, and (c) semantic nearest neighbors from embeddings. Similarity is not transitive, so “A similar to B similar to C” must not become a default relevance claim. Direct neighbors and shared attributes are one-hop SQL joins; vector similarity is already a ranked projection. A normalized `style_relationships(source_style_id, relation, target_style_id NULL, raw_target_label, rationale, resolution_status, confidence, source_hash, generation_id)` table with indexes on `(source_style_id, relation)` and `(target_style_id, relation)` is sufficient now. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405] [INFERENCE: similarity's non-transitivity and the in-repo indexed-adjacency query pattern bound current traversal to one hop]\n6. **Technology recommendation:** ship SQLite + FTS5 + profile-addressed embeddings, with normalized relational edges in the same published SQLite generation. This minimum topology keeps eligibility, metadata, FTS, relationship identity, and generation publication in one transactional snapshot; the vector shard remains a rebuildable generation/profile-bound projection. Compared with it, a dedicated graph database adds native variable-path querying but also a second availability domain, schema/migration surface, backup/restore path, authentication/runtime dependency, projection lag, and cross-store cutover failure modes without a demonstrated style query that benefits. A hybrid with a graph projection preserves relational authority but pays those duplication costs, so it is an optional future topology, not the launch topology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:135-176] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:252-298] [INFERENCE: combining iteration-4 atomic generation publication with the observed derived-projection lifecycle minimizes current failure domains]\n7. The optional future graph must be a rebuildable, generation-stamped projection from relational `style_relationships`, never a second authority. Its failure should disable graph-only ranking/exploration while structured + FTS + vector retrieval remains available; publication must expose projection generation and lag, and rebuild/rollback must be idempotent. This mirrors the council graph's explicit derived-index ownership and namespace cleanup, rather than dual-writing user-authored truth. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:690-705] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:271-298] [INFERENCE: a disposable projection prevents graph outage or lag from corrupting the authoritative generation]\n8. Promote to a dedicated graph projection only when all relevant gates hold: a product query requires explainable variable-depth paths (normally 3+ hops), path constraints, community/centrality algorithms, or cross-entity traversal that cannot be expressed as bounded joins; an indexed SQLite/recursive-CTE benchmark misses the defined p95 SLO at representative edge volume; graph-derived ranking materially improves an offline relevance set; canonical target resolution is identity-based and high-quality (recommended ≥95%, with ambiguity quarantined); and operators have generation parity, lag alarms, rebuild, restore, rollback, and graph-down fallback drills. Until then, graph traversal is an unmeasured capability rather than user value. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:747-805] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:513-547] [INFERENCE: promotion must be justified by workload, relevance, data quality, and operability rather than graph-shaped nouns]\n\n## Ruled Out\n- Dedicated graph database in the minimum topology: no current style query needs native variable-depth traversal, and the corpus relationship targets are mostly unresolved.\n- Treating every `similar.business` label as a canonical edge: 60.96% are ambiguous or unresolved by unique canonical name.\n- Materializing shared facet or embedding similarity as authoritative graph edges: both are derived query signals and would create avoidable churn.\n- Default transitive similarity expansion: the relationship semantics do not support transitivity.\n\n## Dead Ends\n- “Graph data requires a graph server” is eliminated by both named in-repo implementations: they use indexed SQLite adjacency tables and bounded application/SQL queries.\n- Evaluating native graph algorithms before canonical relationship resolution and a concrete multi-hop product query would benchmark an invented workload.\n\n## Edge Cases\n- Ambiguous input: “graph database” could mean any node/edge model or a dedicated graph engine. The comparison uses the dedicated-engine meaning; the in-repo SQLite graph projections are treated as evidence for the relational-edge option.\n- Contradictory evidence: none.\n- Missing dependencies: none; no external graph-service benchmark was needed because selecting one is a stated non-goal and no qualifying workload exists.\n- Partial success: none.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n- `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6,119-176,195-223,658-705`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-227`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-370,935-974`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-805`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-547`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73,391-405`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118`\n- `command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory, 2026-07-19T07:42:08Z`\n\n## Assessment\n- New information ratio: 1.0 (7 fully new findings and 1 partially new schema extension yield 0.9375; resolving Q1 adds the 0.10 simplicity bonus, capped at 1.0).\n- Questions addressed: Q1.\n- Questions answered: Q1.\n- Convergence: telemetry only; the max-iterations policy still requires iterations 8-10.\n\n## Reflection\n- What worked and why: reading the graph storage and query modules together separated graph data modeling from graph-engine necessity; quantifying the corpus's actual `similar` payload prevented a topology recommendation based on assumed relationship quality.\n- What did not work and why: a broad relationship-key search was noisy because `similar` appears in nearly every canonical file; the bounded parser converted that noise into resolution and topology measurements.\n- What I would do differently: benchmark a concrete bounded SQLite relationship query only after target normalization rules and a user-facing multi-hop query are specified; benchmarking synthetic traversal now would manufacture demand.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\nPressure-test the recommended single-generation topology against concurrency, database/vector file placement, startup/cold-cache latency, corruption boundaries, backup size, and graph-down-equivalent degradation; define measurable SLOs that could activate the graph-promotion gates without reopening Q1 by preference.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":54,"totalLines":54,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-007.md","time":{"start":1784447122028,"end":1784447122039}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0605df8c7dafe349016a5c8091f2d88191afe596f7cecdd9f8"}},"id":"prt_f79563a58001r4YS6moLjAct3A","sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","messageID":"msg_f79561e990013aueidIUr8osr5"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784447122138,"sessionID":"ses_086d7cfc0ffe217XO92sKCjWRm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_eks82oaJ02go2jryLhcJshsk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deltas/iter-007.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/001-research-style-database/research/lineages/sol/deltas/iter-007.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":7,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":7,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Resolve Q1 by comparing SQLite plus FTS5 and embeddings, a dedicated graph database, and a hybrid graph projection; determine required traversal, operational trade-offs, minimum topology, and graph-promotion conditions.\",\"findingsCount\":8,\"newInfoRatio\":1.0,\"noveltyJustification\":\"7 of 8 findings were fully new and 1 was partially new; resolving Q1 added the 0.10 simplicity bonus, capped at 1.0.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Q1\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Q1\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Dedicated graph database in the minimum topology\",\"Treating unresolved similar labels as canonical edges\",\"Materializing shared facets or vector similarity as authoritative edges\",\"Default transitive similarity expansion\"],\"focusTrack\":\"topology-graph-boundary\",\"edgeCase\":\"ambiguous-input\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Grep\",\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\",\"ApplyPatch\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:18-41\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:3-8\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:7-94\",\"research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:1-85\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:1-6,119-176,195-223,658-705\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:159-227\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-370,935-974\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:565-805\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-547\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73,391-405\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118\",\"command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory\",\"command: date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ\"],\"t... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n2: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F1\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Canonical styles contain explained similar-business candidates that the current retrieval projection omits.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:43-73\"]}\n3: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F2\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Only 2269 of 5812 similar labels resolve to one canonical style name; unresolved and ambiguous targets must remain quarantined.\",\"sources\":[\"command: bounded Node canonical-style relationship inventory\"]}\n4: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F3\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Both named in-repo graph databases are normalized SQLite adjacency projections with indexed endpoints and transactional writes.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:119-176\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:234-298\"]}\n5: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F4\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Graph query contracts are mostly one-hop SQL; multi-hop evidence/provenance paths are bounded application BFS and DAG depth.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-query.ts:191-227\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-699\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:413-469\"]}\n6: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F5\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Style relationship needs are direct similar neighbors, shared relational attributes, and vector neighbors; similarity is not transitively authoritative.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/shade/shade-canonical.json:102-118\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/manifest.mjs:391-405\"]}\n7: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F6\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Minimum production topology is one published SQLite generation with FTS5 and normalized edges plus a profile-addressed vector projection.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:135-176\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:252-298\"]}\n8: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F7\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Any future graph is a rebuildable generation-stamped projection with graph-down fallback, never an authority.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:3-4\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/council/council-graph-db.ts:690-705\"]}\n9: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"I007-F8\",\"iteration\":7,\"summary\":\"Graph promotion requires a measured variable-depth workload, SQLite SLO failure, relevance lift, identity-quality readiness, and projection operations.\",\"sources\":[\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-query.ts:644-805\",\".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-signals.ts:513-547\"]}\n\n(End of file - total 9 lines)\n</conte